{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582701"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:52:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:52:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"638"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/638"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.91,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"638"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102261"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/638"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"638"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84725"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"492"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6099"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35702"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102261"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old woman presents to the operating room of a public hospital for an elective cholecystectomy. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring the procedure, the trainee damages the common bile duct. The consultant is called, corrects the situation, and converts the laparoscopic procedure to an open operation, resulting in a long right subcostal incision.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate way of dealing with this situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The supervising surgeon should document the error in the medical record and notify hospital risk management","The trainee should tell the patient that this was a well-recognised complication","The supervising surgeon should disclose the situation to the patient empathetically","The surgeon should ensure that a lawyer is present during the discussion with the patient","Neither surgeon should apologise as it may complicate future legal proceedings"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDespite the trainee making the error, the \u003Cstrong\u003Esupervising surgeon ultimately has responsibility\u003C/strong\u003E for the care of patients in a public teaching hospital. The trainee appropriately escalated the issue, and the consultant was on site to assist when required. For this reason, the consultant should disclose the error to the patient. It would also be reasonable for the trainee to also be present during the disclosure process, as open disclosure is an important skill for trainees to develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe supervising surgeon should document the error in the medical record and notify hospital risk management\u003C/strong\u003E is a plausible step in the process of managing a complication, but it does not replace the ethical and legal requirement for open disclosure to the patient. Documentation and notification are important, but direct, honest communication with the patient is always essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe trainee should tell the patient that this was a well-recognised complication\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate approach. While bile duct injury is a known risk, the responsibility for disclosure lies with the supervising surgeon, who should lead the discussion and ensure the patient is fully informed. Delegating this to the trainee alone may undermine the seriousness of the event. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA lawyer does not need to be present\u003C/strong\u003E during disclosure of medical errors. Legal representation is not required for disclosure of medical error, and involving a lawyer at this stage may undermine trust and communication with the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApologising in this circumstance is not an admission of guilt\u003C/strong\u003E, but rather a recognition that a complication has occurred, which may affect the patient\u0027s recovery. The rapport built during honest conversations such as this, will often result in a more trusting doctor patient relationship, and less likely to be litigious in nature. Withholding an apology can damage rapport and is not supported by current ethical or legal standards.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Full disclosure of medical error is required by law and ethical practice.","The supervising surgeon holds ultimate responsibility for patient care and disclosure in a teaching hospital.","Empathetic communication, including an apology, is essential and does not constitute an admission of legal liability."],"references":["Gallagher T. Content of Medical Error Disclosures. AMA Journal of Ethics. 2004;6(3).","Braunack-Mayer A, Mintzker Y. General practice ethics: Disclosing errors. Aust Fam Physician. 2015;44(12):939-940."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84725"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"638"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84725"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-11T10:04:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-11T10:04:36+09:30"},"relationsh